{
  "local_port": 51118,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I do not have a surname on passport or any of my education certificates. What should be the most appropriate step now to fix the issue?",
  "response": "Not having a surname on your passport or education certificates can create complications, especially when applying for visas, jobs, or other official documents. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to resolve the issue:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand the Problem**\n   - In some cultures or countries, surnames are optional or not traditionally used. However, many systems require a surname for identification purposes.\n   - Check your local laws or passport authority regulations to confirm if a surname is mandatory.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Consult the Passport Office**\n   - Contact the passport issuing authority in your country (e.g., the Passport Seva Kendra in India or the Department of State in the U.S.).\n   - Explain your situation and inquire about the process to add a surname to your passport.\n   - You may need to provide evidence, such as a legal affidavit, birth certificate, or other supporting documents.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Add a Surname Legally**\n   - If you don\u2019t have a surname, consider adopting one legally. This could be your father\u2019s name, family name, or any name of your choice.\n   - In some cases, you can use your given name (first name) as your surname or repeat your first name as the surname (e.g., \"John John\").\n   - File a legal affidavit or deed poll to formalize the adoption of a surname.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Update Your Education Certificates**\n   - Once you\u2019ve added a surname to your passport, contact the institutions that issued your education certificates.\n   - Request corrections or updates to include your surname, providing your updated passport as proof.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Use a Consistent Name Across Documents**\n   - Ensure your name (including the surname) is consistent across all official documents, such as passports, PAN cards, Aadhaar cards, driver\u2019s licenses, and education certificates.\n   - This consistency will avoid confusion in future applications.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Seek Legal Advice if Needed**\n   - If the process is unclear or complex, consult a legal expert or lawyer specializing in name changes or document corrections.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Consider Cultural or Personal Preferences**\n   - If surnames are not culturally significant for you, you may still need to comply with official requirements. For example:\n     - Use your father\u2019s or family name as a surname.\n     - Use a single name (e.g., \"Mononym\") if allowed by your country\u2019s passport authority.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Apply for Corrections**\n   - Once you\u2019ve decided on a surname, apply for corrections or reissuance of your passport and other documents. Be prepared to:\n     - Pay applicable fees.\n     - Submit supporting documents (e.g., affidavit, birth certificate, etc.).\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Update Other Systems**\n   - After updating your passport and education certificates, inform other institutions (e.g., banks, employers, etc.) of the name change to ensure alignment.\n\n---\n\nBy addressing this issue proactively, you can avoid future complications and ensure your documents are accepted internationally.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
